or so in crusing velocity between stars. The .10 c maximium starship velocity should be considered to be standard for fusion drives on interstellar round trips. On one way decelerated missions a maximium delta v of .20 C might be achieved if you were to stack 3 5/1 mass ratio fusion stages on top of each other and the specific impulse is 3,000,000<br>
seconds. The maximium delta v (crusing velocity )  for fission powered interstellar rockets is .03 c to .05 C .<br>
<br>
Antimatter - Matter annhilation powered interstellar rockets<br>
can achieve a maximium delta v of from .50 C to perhaps<br>
.80 C or so. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 475<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/15/02 3:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=49.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: interstellar nuclear rocket powered starships</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Antimatter - Matter annhilation powered interstellar rockets<br>
