.80 C or so.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Definitly fast enough for time dilation to take effect, you could<br>
explore much of the milky way at .8 C <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 117<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/15/02 4:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=49.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: interstellar nuclear rocket powered starships</span><hr size=1> I haven't checked the adequacy of the calculations above about max velocity, but assuming a velocity  of only 0.8 c, its not going to buy you much time.<br>
<br>
Time dilation at that speed is only 1.67. That means  1 2/3 Earth years pass for every ship year.<br>
<br>
So, at 0.8 c it takes 5 years to reach Alpha Centuri. To the star traveler, 3 years will pass. <br>
<br>
Definitely saves some pit stops, but far from enuff to sail the galaxy.<br>
<br>
  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujdstokes.showPublicProfile?language=EN>jdstokes</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/15/02 10:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=49.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Laser sailing</span><hr size=1> The only other alternative is the laser-pushed light sail.<br>
This involves a large array of solar-pumped lasers beaming energy to a large, lightweight fresnel lens held stationary out beyond the orbit of Neptune, along the line of sight between the center of the nearby target star and sol.<br>
<br>
A spacecraft with solar sail furled can now navigate into this beam using nuclear pulse rockets.  Once in the beam, the sail is unfurled and the spacecraft accelerates at 1 gee for 6 months.  The spacecraft then furls the sail and coasts to the target star at c/2.<br>
<br>
To decelerate, the craft generates a mini-magnetosphere (based on the work of Winglee et al) to create drag by deflecting the ambient plasma of the interstellar medium.<br>
<br>
Once slowed to planetary speeds, the craft uses advanced nuclear pulse rockets to navigate throughout the target star's system of objects.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 121<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/15/02 11:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=49.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Laser sailing</span><hr size=1> I don't see the need for coupling the system with a atomic bomb engine. An ion engine driven by solar or nuclear energy gives comparable Isp's without the wasteful heavy structure and inefficiency in fuel utilization. The whole pulse system would just be a huge expense in terms of mass ratios. <br>
<br>
In any event why not use a solar sail from the get-go? Lasered or mirrored sunlight would of course be frosting on the cake.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujdstokes.showPublicProfile?language=EN>jdstokes</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/16/02 2:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=49.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Laser sailing</span><hr size=1> Because nuclear pulse has higher thrust to weight, and a higher Isp.  It is very unlike the original nuclear pulse rocket concepts of the 1950s - as it incorporates the very latest in nuclear technologies.  Operating at<br>
50,000 second Isp, with a T/W of 15.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 123<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/16/02 4:45 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=49.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Laser sailing</span><hr size=1> Please supply referenced details of those Isp and T/W numbers.<br>
