<br>
By containing a microfission blast with powerful magnetic fields, similar to those used for inertial confinement fusion research, a Ve of 1,000,000 m/sec would be attainable.<br>
<br>
If pure microfusion could be achieved, Ve would climb to about 20,000,000 m/sec and there would be no residual radiation it the exhaust. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 125<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/16/02 10:24 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=49.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Laser sailing</span><hr size=1> The only references I could track down from those sources are for speculative designs using anti-matter to boost the fission.<br>
<br>
